<p><br></p>
<p>The Duke Gardens <a href="https://twitter.com/DukeGardens/status/1041727803790639106" target="_blank">announced</a> that it will be closed until noon on Tuesday to "assess hazardous conditions due to flooding or other damage." The Gardens could be seen inundated Monday.&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
<!--ceo:replacemode=raw-->




    <figure style="max-width:100%;    " class="embedded-media embedded-image">
        
        <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/f3469114-4bc8-4e8d-a555-9d32eff1e872.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" class="w-100" alt="" />                    <span class="embedded-credit">
                                    <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/bre-bradham">Bre Bradham</a>                                            </span>
                    </figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Other areas in the Carolinas were impacted more severely than Duke, Moneta added in his email. &nbsp;</p>
<p>"The aftermath of the rains and winds will be felt for quite a long time and some parts of these states have yet to even reach their peak flooding," Moneta wrote. "Property damages and personal losses will be extreme but the emotional toll this will take is immeasurable."</p>

